{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UJupgiEneZtzXK8qcGLwLE","type":"tool_result","content":"     1ŌåÆ/**\n     2ŌåÆ * Verification prompt template for black-box verifier sessions.\n     3ŌåÆ * Architecture Decision 6: All templates are TypeScript string literals.\n     4ŌåÆ * Architecture Decision 10: Two-layer isolation ŌĆö clean workspace + Docker container.\n     5ŌåÆ *\n     6ŌåÆ * This prompt is passed to `claude --print -p \"...\"` in a clean workspace\n     7ŌåÆ * that contains NO source code. The verifier must exercise the feature\n     8ŌåÆ * exclusively via `docker exec` and observability queries.\n     9ŌåÆ */\n    10ŌåÆ\n    11ŌåÆexport type PromptProjectType = 'nodejs' | 'python' | 'plugin' | 'generic';\n    12ŌåÆ\n    13ŌåÆexport interface VerifyPromptConfig {\n    14ŌåÆ  /** Story key, e.g. \"13-3-black-box-verifier-agent\" */\n    15ŌåÆ  storyKey: string;\n    16ŌåÆ  /** Full content of story.md from the clean workspace */\n    17ŌåÆ  storyContent: string;\n    18ŌåÆ  /** Docker container name (default: \"codeharness-verify\") */\n    19ŌåÆ  containerName?: string;\n    20ŌåÆ  /** Project type for verification strategy guidance */\n    21ŌåÆ  projectType?: PromptProjectType;\n    22ŌåÆ  /** Observability endpoint overrides */\n    23ŌåÆ  observabilityEndpoints?: {\n    24ŌåÆ    victoriaLogs?: string;\n    25ŌåÆ    victoriaMetrics?: string;\n    26ŌåÆ    victoriaTraces?: string;\n    27ŌåÆ  };\n    28ŌåÆ}\n    29ŌåÆ\n    30ŌåÆconst DEFAULT_CONTAINER = 'codeharness-verify';\n    31ŌåÆ\n    32ŌåÆconst DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS = {\n    33ŌåÆ  victoriaLogs: 'http://localhost:9428',\n    34ŌåÆ  victoriaMetrics: 'http://localhost:8428',\n    35ŌåÆ  victoriaTraces: 'http://localhost:16686',\n    36ŌåÆ};\n    37ŌåÆ\n    38ŌåÆ/** Returns project-type-specific verification guidance. */\n    39ŌåÆexport function projectTypeGuidance(projectType: PromptProjectType, container: string): string {\n    40ŌåÆ  switch (projectType) {\n    41ŌåÆ    case 'nodejs':\n    42ŌåÆ    case 'python':\n    43ŌåÆ      return `### Project Type: ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js CLI' : 'Python CLI'}\n    44ŌåÆ\n    45ŌåÆExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n    46ŌåÆ- \\`docker exec ${container} <cli-command> [args]\\`\n    47ŌåÆ- Capture exit codes: \\`docker exec ${container} sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'\\`\n    48ŌåÆ- For ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js' : 'Python'} projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.`;\n    49ŌåÆ\n    50ŌåÆ    case 'plugin':\n    51ŌåÆ      return `### Project Type: Claude Code Plugin\n    52ŌåÆ\n    53ŌåÆThis is a Claude Code plugin project. Verify using \\`claude --print\\` inside the container:\n    54ŌåÆ- \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print -p \"<prompt>\" --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n    55ŌåÆ- Plugin commands and hooks are installed in the container's Claude Code environment.\n    56ŌåÆ- Test slash commands by prompting Claude to run them inside the container.`;\n    57ŌåÆ\n    58ŌåÆ    case 'generic':\n    59ŌåÆ      return `### Project Type: Unknown / Generic\n    60ŌåÆ\n    61ŌåÆThe project stack was not recognized. Adapt your verification approach to the tools available:\n    62ŌåÆ- Use basic CLI tools: \\`bash\\`, \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\`, \\`node\\`\n    63ŌåÆ- Inspect any artifacts copied into the container\n    64ŌåÆ- If the project provides a CLI binary, test it directly\n    65ŌåÆ- Adapt to whatever tools and artifacts are available ŌĆö do not refuse verification`;\n    66ŌåÆ  }\n    67ŌåÆ}\n    68ŌåÆ\n    69ŌåÆ/**\n    70ŌåÆ * Generates the verification prompt for a black-box verifier session.\n    71ŌåÆ * The prompt instructs the verifier to:\n    72ŌåÆ * - Read README.md for usage guidance\n    73ŌåÆ * - Run ALL commands via `docker exec`\n    74ŌåÆ * - Query observability endpoints for runtime evidence\n    75ŌåÆ * - Write a proof document at `verification/{storyKey}-proof.md`\n    76ŌåÆ * - Report REAL failures ŌĆö never fabricate evidence\n    77ŌåÆ */\n    78ŌåÆexport function verifyPromptTemplate(config: VerifyPromptConfig): string {\n    79ŌåÆ  const container = config.containerName ?? DEFAULT_CONTAINER;\n    80ŌåÆ  const projectType = config.projectType ?? 'nodejs';\n    81ŌåÆ  const endpoints = {\n    82ŌåÆ    ...DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS,\n    83ŌåÆ    ...config.observabilityEndpoints,\n    84ŌåÆ  };\n    85ŌåÆ\n    86ŌåÆ  return `You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective ŌĆö using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n    87ŌåÆ\n    88ŌåÆ## Why Black-Box Verification\n    89ŌåÆ\n    90ŌåÆThis workspace contains NO source code. The \\`src/\\` directory does not exist. This is intentional ŌĆö you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n    91ŌåÆ\n    92ŌåÆ## Step 1: Read README.md\n    93ŌåÆ\n    94ŌåÆStart by reading \\`README.md\\` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n    95ŌåÆ\n    96ŌåÆ## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n    97ŌåÆ\n    98ŌåÆThe story file \\`story.md\\` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Here is its content:\n    99ŌåÆ\n   100ŌåÆ---\n   101ŌåÆ${config.storyContent}\n   102ŌåÆ---\n   103ŌåÆ\n   104ŌåÆ## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n   105ŌåÆ\n   106ŌåÆFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n   107ŌåÆ\n   108ŌåÆ1. Run commands inside the Docker container via \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`\n   109ŌåÆ2. Capture the command output as evidence\n   110ŌåÆ3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n   111ŌåÆ4. For ACs that involve Claude Code sessions or agent workflows, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude ...\\` to spawn real sessions inside the container\n   112ŌåÆ\n   113ŌåÆ### Docker Container\n   114ŌåÆ\n   115ŌåÆ- Container name: \\`${container}\\`\n   116ŌåÆ- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: \\`docker exec ${container} <command>\\`\n   117ŌåÆ- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness --version\\`\n   118ŌåÆ- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness init --json\\`\n   119ŌåÆ- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"Run /harness-run\" --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n   120ŌåÆ\n   121ŌåÆThe container has the following tools installed:\n   122ŌåÆ- \\`codeharness\\` ŌĆö the project CLI\n   123ŌåÆ- \\`claude\\` ŌĆö Claude Code CLI (authenticated via ANTHROPIC_API_KEY env var)\n   124ŌåÆ- \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\` ŌĆö for querying observability endpoints\n   125ŌåÆ- \\`showboat\\` ŌĆö for proof document validation\n   126ŌåÆ- \\`node\\`, \\`npm\\` ŌĆö Node.js runtime\n   127ŌåÆ\n   128ŌåÆ**IMPORTANT: When invoking \\`claude --print\\` inside Docker, always pass \\`--allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit\\` to prevent the nested session from hanging on tool permission prompts.**\n   129ŌåÆ\n   130ŌåÆ${projectTypeGuidance(projectType, container)}\n   131ŌåÆ\n   132ŌåÆ### Observability Endpoints\n   133ŌåÆ\n   134ŌåÆQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n   135ŌåÆ\n   136ŌåÆ- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): \\`${endpoints.victoriaLogs}\\`\n   137ŌåÆ  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'\\`\n   138ŌåÆ- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): \\`${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}\\`\n   139ŌåÆ  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}/api/v1/query?query=up'\\`\n   140ŌåÆ- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): \\`${endpoints.victoriaTraces}\\`\n   141ŌåÆ  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaTraces}/api/traces?service=codeharness-verify&limit=10'\\`\n   142ŌåÆ\n   143ŌåÆ## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n   144ŌåÆ\n   145ŌåÆAfter EACH \\`docker exec\\` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n   146ŌåÆ\n   147ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`bash\n   148ŌåÆcurl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n   149ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`\n   150ŌåÆ\n   151ŌåÆ- If the response contains **one or more log entries**, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n   152ŌåÆ- If the response contains **zero log entries**, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag in the AC section of your proof:\n   153ŌåÆ\n   154ŌåÆ  \\`[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction\\`\n   155ŌåÆ\n   156ŌåÆThis check detects silent code paths ŌĆö places where the application runs but produces no telemetry. Every AC should produce some log output when exercised.\n   157ŌåÆ\n   158ŌåÆ## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n   159ŌåÆ\n   160ŌåÆWrite your verification proof to: \\`verification/${config.storyKey}-proof.md\\`\n   161ŌåÆ\n   162ŌåÆUse this format for each AC:\n   163ŌåÆ\n   164ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`markdown\n   165ŌåÆ## AC N: <description>\n   166ŌåÆ\n   167ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`bash\n   168ŌåÆdocker exec ${container} <command>\n   169ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`\n   170ŌåÆ\n   171ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`output\n   172ŌåÆ<actual output>\n   173ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`\n   174ŌåÆ\\`\\`\\`\n   175ŌåÆ\n   176ŌåÆ**IMPORTANT: Only use \\`bash\\` and \\`output\\` as code fence languages.** Never use bare \\`\\`\\` fences without a language tag. If quoting code snippets, use \\`\\`\\`text. Showboat will try to execute any unlabeled code block.\n   177ŌåÆ\n   178ŌåÆ## Critical Rules\n   179ŌåÆ\n   180ŌåÆ1. **ALL commands MUST use \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`** ŌĆö do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n   181ŌåÆ2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** ŌĆö there is no \\`src/\\` directory in this workspace. If you try to \\`grep\\`, \\`cat\\`, or \\`find\\` source files, you will find nothing.\n   182ŌåÆ3. **Report REAL failures** ŌĆö if a feature does not work via the CLI or the documentation is insufficient to exercise it, report that as a verification failure with specific details about what went wrong. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n   183ŌåÆ4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** ŌĆö reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n   184ŌåÆ5. **Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.** If an AC has 5 parts and you can verify 4, verify those 4 and escalate ONLY the specific part you cannot reach. Never blanket-escalate an entire AC because one aspect requires something unavailable.\n   185ŌåÆ6. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** ŌĆö physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems (missing binary, wrong version, tree-shaking, Docker config) are NOT valid escalation reasons. If a tool is missing from the container, that is a bug to report as [FAIL], not an [ESCALATE]. The harness will fix the infrastructure and re-verify.\n   186ŌåÆ7. **\\`claude\\` CLI is available** inside the container. If an AC requires spawning a Claude Code session, running a slash command, or testing agent behavior, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"...\" --max-budget-usd 1\\` to actually test it. Do NOT escalate just because \"it needs a Claude session.\"\n   187ŌåÆ8. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL] ŌĆö don't fall back to running tests on the host. The harness-run flow will fix the Docker problem and retry.\n   188ŌåÆ`;\n   189ŌåÆ}\n   190ŌåÆ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d06dabce-ed3c-4abf-ad84-f2845532d39a","uuid":"c1c52182-5334-4bc9-a66d-0e42c2ee4e0c","timestamp":"2026-03-21T05:07:37.382Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/templates/verify-prompt.ts","content":"/**\n * Verification prompt template for black-box verifier sessions.\n * Architecture Decision 6: All templates are TypeScript string literals.\n * Architecture Decision 10: Two-layer isolation ŌĆö clean workspace + Docker container.\n *\n * This prompt is passed to `claude --print -p \"...\"` in a clean workspace\n * that contains NO source code. The verifier must exercise the feature\n * exclusively via `docker exec` and observability queries.\n */\n\nexport type PromptProjectType = 'nodejs' | 'python' | 'plugin' | 'generic';\n\nexport interface VerifyPromptConfig {\n  /** Story key, e.g. \"13-3-black-box-verifier-agent\" */\n  storyKey: string;\n  /** Full content of story.md from the clean workspace */\n  storyContent: string;\n  /** Docker container name (default: \"codeharness-verify\") */\n  containerName?: string;\n  /** Project type for verification strategy guidance */\n  projectType?: PromptProjectType;\n  /** Observability endpoint overrides */\n  observabilityEndpoints?: {\n    victoriaLogs?: string;\n    victoriaMetrics?: string;\n    victoriaTraces?: string;\n  };\n}\n\nconst DEFAULT_CONTAINER = 'codeharness-verify';\n\nconst DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS = {\n  victoriaLogs: 'http://localhost:9428',\n  victoriaMetrics: 'http://localhost:8428',\n  victoriaTraces: 'http://localhost:16686',\n};\n\n/** Returns project-type-specific verification guidance. */\nexport function projectTypeGuidance(projectType: PromptProjectType, container: string): string {\n  switch (projectType) {\n    case 'nodejs':\n    case 'python':\n      return `### Project Type: ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js CLI' : 'Python CLI'}\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- \\`docker exec ${container} <cli-command> [args]\\`\n- Capture exit codes: \\`docker exec ${container} sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'\\`\n- For ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js' : 'Python'} projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.`;\n\n    case 'plugin':\n      return `### Project Type: Claude Code Plugin\n\nThis is a Claude Code plugin project. Verify using \\`claude --print\\` inside the container:\n- \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print -p \"<prompt>\" --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n- Plugin commands and hooks are installed in the container's Claude Code environment.\n- Test slash commands by prompting Claude to run them inside the container.`;\n\n    case 'generic':\n      return `### Project Type: Unknown / Generic\n\nThe project stack was not recognized. Adapt your verification approach to the tools available:\n- Use basic CLI tools: \\`bash\\`, \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\`, \\`node\\`\n- Inspect any artifacts copied into the container\n- If the project provides a CLI binary, test it directly\n- Adapt to whatever tools and artifacts are available ŌĆö do not refuse verification`;\n  }\n}\n\n/**\n * Generates the verification prompt for a black-box verifier session.\n * The prompt instructs the verifier to:\n * - Read README.md for usage guidance\n * - Run ALL commands via `docker exec`\n * - Query observability endpoints for runtime evidence\n * - Write a proof document at `verification/{storyKey}-proof.md`\n * - Report REAL failures ŌĆö never fabricate evidence\n */\nexport function verifyPromptTemplate(config: VerifyPromptConfig): string {\n  const container = config.containerName ?? DEFAULT_CONTAINER;\n  const projectType = config.projectType ?? 'nodejs';\n  const endpoints = {\n    ...DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS,\n    ...config.observabilityEndpoints,\n  };\n\n  return `You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective ŌĆö using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The \\`src/\\` directory does not exist. This is intentional ŌĆö you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading \\`README.md\\` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file \\`story.md\\` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Here is its content:\n\n---\n${config.storyContent}\n---\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n4. For ACs that involve Claude Code sessions or agent workflows, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude ...\\` to spawn real sessions inside the container\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: \\`${container}\\`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: \\`docker exec ${container} <command>\\`\n- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness --version\\`\n- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness init --json\\`\n- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"Run /harness-run\" --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- \\`codeharness\\` ŌĆö the project CLI\n- \\`claude\\` ŌĆö Claude Code CLI (authenticated via ANTHROPIC_API_KEY env var)\n- \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\` ŌĆö for querying observability endpoints\n- \\`showboat\\` ŌĆö for proof document validation\n- \\`node\\`, \\`npm\\` ŌĆö Node.js runtime\n\n**IMPORTANT: When invoking \\`claude --print\\` inside Docker, always pass \\`--allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit\\` to prevent the nested session from hanging on tool permission prompts.**\n\n${projectTypeGuidance(projectType, container)}\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): \\`${endpoints.victoriaLogs}\\`\n  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'\\`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): \\`${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}\\`\n  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}/api/v1/query?query=up'\\`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): \\`${endpoints.victoriaTraces}\\`\n  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaTraces}/api/traces?service=codeharness-verify&limit=10'\\`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH \\`docker exec\\` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\ncurl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n- If the response contains **one or more log entries**, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains **zero log entries**, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag in the AC section of your proof:\n\n  \\`[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction\\`\n\nThis check detects silent code paths ŌĆö places where the application runs but produces no telemetry. Every AC should produce some log output when exercised.\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: \\`verification/${config.storyKey}-proof.md\\`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n\\`\\`\\`markdown\n## AC N: <description>\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\ndocker exec ${container} <command>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n\\`\\`\\`output\n<actual output>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use \\`bash\\` and \\`output\\` as code fence languages.** Never use bare \\`\\`\\` fences without a language tag. If quoting code snippets, use \\`\\`\\`text. Showboat will try to execute any unlabeled code block.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`** ŌĆö do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** ŌĆö there is no \\`src/\\` directory in this workspace. If you try to \\`grep\\`, \\`cat\\`, or \\`find\\` source files, you will find nothing.\n3. **Report REAL failures** ŌĆö if a feature does not work via the CLI or the documentation is insufficient to exercise it, report that as a verification failure with specific details about what went wrong. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** ŌĆö reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. **Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.** If an AC has 5 parts and you can verify 4, verify those 4 and escalate ONLY the specific part you cannot reach. Never blanket-escalate an entire AC because one aspect requires something unavailable.\n6. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** ŌĆö physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems (missing binary, wrong version, tree-shaking, Docker config) are NOT valid escalation reasons. If a tool is missing from the container, that is a bug to report as [FAIL], not an [ESCALATE]. The harness will fix the infrastructure and re-verify.\n7. **\\`claude\\` CLI is available** inside the container. If an AC requires spawning a Claude Code session, running a slash command, or testing agent behavior, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"...\" --max-budget-usd 1\\` to actually test it. Do NOT escalate just because \"it needs a Claude session.\"\n8. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL] ŌĆö don't fall back to running tests on the host. The harness-run flow will fix the Docker problem and retry.\n`;\n}\n","numLines":190,"startLine":1,"totalLines":190}}}
