{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01NJnojhBktYubesDySsFK7P","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SjgDG6jEEFREtDac2tKMjd","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/codeharness-verify-3-3-onboard-alias/verify-prompt.txt << 'PROMPT_EOF'\nYou are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective ŌĆö using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional ŌĆö you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file `story.md` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Read it now.\n\nThere are 8 ACs to verify for story 3-3-onboard-alias:\n\n1. `codeharness onboard` (no flags) produces identical output to `codeharness audit`\n2. `codeharness onboard --fix` produces identical output to `codeharness audit --fix`\n3. `codeharness onboard --json` produces identical JSON to `codeharness audit --json`\n4. `codeharness onboard --fix --json` produces identical output to `codeharness audit --fix --json`\n5. When harness not initialized, `codeharness onboard` exits with `[FAIL] Harness not initialized -- run codeharness init first` and exit code 1\n6. `codeharness onboard scan` prints deprecation warning and runs audit\n7. Old registerOnboardCommand replaced by alias registration (no duplicate)\n8. `codeharness --help` shows both `audit` and `onboard` commands\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n\nThe container has:\n- `codeharness` ŌĆö the project CLI\n- `curl`, `jq` ŌĆö for querying observability endpoints\n- `node`, `npm` ŌĆö Node.js runtime\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): `http://localhost:9428`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): `http://localhost:8428`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): `http://localhost:16686`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n```\n\n- If the response contains one or more log entries, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains zero log entries, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag in the AC section of your proof:\n  `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction`\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `verification/3-3-onboard-alias-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```text\n## AC N: <description>\n\n**Verdict: PASS | FAIL | [ESCALATE]**\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages.** Never use bare ``` fences without a language tag. If quoting code snippets, use ```text. Showboat will try to execute any unlabeled code block.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...` ŌĆö do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. Do NOT attempt to access source code ŌĆö there is no `src/` directory in this workspace.\n3. Report REAL failures ŌĆö if a feature does not work, report that as a verification failure with specific details.\n4. Every AC needs functional evidence ŌĆö reading docs alone is not evidence.\n5. Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.\n6. [ESCALATE] is ONLY for things genuinely impossible to automate ŌĆö physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment.\n7. Never switch to unit-testable verification. Report WHY as [FAIL] if Docker verification doesn't work.\n\n## Verification Strategy for This Story\n\nFor ACs 1-4 and 6: Run both the `audit` and `onboard` commands and compare their outputs. They should be identical (or for AC6, include the deprecation warning before audit output).\n\nFor AC5: Run in a directory without harness initialization and check the error message and exit code.\n\nFor AC7: This is about source code structure ŌĆö but you can verify it indirectly by confirming that both commands work and there are no duplicate command registrations (check `codeharness --help` shows each command exactly once).\n\nFor AC8: Run `codeharness --help` and verify both commands appear with correct descriptions.\n\nIMPORTANT: For AC5, to test in an uninitialized directory, use:\n`docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'cd /tmp && codeharness onboard 2>&1; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\nSimilarly for audit comparison:\n`docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'cd /tmp && codeharness audit 2>&1; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n\nFor ACs 1-4, you need an initialized project. First check if one exists in the container, or use `codeharness init` to create one in a temp directory.\nPROMPT_EOF\necho \"Prompt written successfully\"","description":"Write verification prompt to file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5054,"cache_read_input_tokens":49280,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5054},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d06dabce-ed3c-4abf-ad84-f2845532d39a","uuid":"b9dd4912-278f-4fab-bcd4-98fa9e6c4080"}
